---
import DocsLayout from "@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CommandBlock from "@/components/ui/CommandBlock.tsx";

const cards = [
  { title: "Installation", href: "/docs/installation/", body: "Clone, install, and check your setup with careeros doctor." },
  { title: "Quick start", href: "/docs/quick-start/", body: "Build your profile once, then run your first daily pipeline." },
  { title: "Configuration", href: "/docs/configuration/", body: "Providers, thresholds, prompt versions, and credentials." },
  { title: "Commands", href: "/docs/commands/", body: "Every command, from careeros daily to the per-stage developer tools." },
  { title: "Architecture", href: "/docs/architecture/", body: "The pipeline, the schemas, and the deterministic/reasoning split." },
  { title: "Contributing", href: "/docs/contributing/", body: "Add a provider, improve a prompt, and respect the core boundary." },
];
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Overview"
  description="CareerOS finds jobs, scores them against your real experience, and writes the results into a Google Sheet you open every morning."
>
  <p>
    CareerOS is an AI-powered, deterministic job discovery and recommendation
    engine. It is <strong>not an application bot</strong>. It sources roles,
    filters and scores them, and drafts the artifacts you need — but you stay in
    the loop and do the applying.
  </p>
  <p>
    The whole system is built around one rule: <strong>use deterministic code
    wherever possible, and AI only where reasoning genuinely adds value.</strong>
    Discovery, deduplication, thresholding, and the daily report are plain code
    that costs zero tokens. AI is spent on exactly two things that need judgment:
    a cheap triage gate, and one real evaluation per job that survives it.
  </p>

  <h2>The shape of a day</h2>
  <CommandBlock
    client:visible
    label="a typical run"
    code={`$ careeros daily   # discover, score, draft, and fill your Sheet\n\n#  → discovered 84 jobs across 3 providers\n#  → 61 unique after dedupe\n#  → 47 passed hard constraints\n#  → 12 kept by the gate\n#  → 12 evaluated (7 from cache)\n#  → 3 Apply, 4 Consider, written to your Sheet`}
  />
  <p>
    The numbers above illustrate the funnel; your run's counts will differ. You
    open the Sheet, read the score and one-line reason for each job, and start
    applying to the ones worth your time.
  </p>

  <h2>Where to go next</h2>
  <div class="mt-6 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 not-prose">
    {
      cards.map((c) => (
        <a href={c.href} class="group flex flex-col rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface p-5 transition-colors hover:border-border-strong">
          <span class="text-[15px] font-semibold text-ink">{c.title}</span>
          <span class="mt-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted">{c.body}</span>
        </a>
      ))
    }
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
